{"id":"project-LICHEN-6zho","title":"announce.c: Signature not zeroed after use - potential cryptographic leak","description":"File: lichen/subsys/lichen/routing/announce.c
Lines: 82 vs 498

In pubkey_to_iid() (line 82), the hash is properly zeroed after use:
    memset(hash, 0, sizeof(hash));

But in build_announce_frame(), the signature buffer (line 498) is never zeroed:
    uint8_t signature[LICHEN_ANNOUNCE_SIGNATURE_LEN];
    ...
    ret = schnorr48_sign(..., signature);
    ...
    memcpy(&buf[pos], signature, LICHEN_ANNOUNCE_SIGNATURE_LEN);

The signature remains in stack memory after the function returns. While this is a lower risk than leaking private keys, it could potentially be extracted via:
1. Stack inspection by debugger
2. Memory dump on crash
3. Subsequent stack frame reuse not fully overwriting

Best practice for cryptographic code: zero sensitive temporaries after use with explicit_bzero() or volatile memset.","status":"open","priority":2,"issue_type":"bug","owner":"me@mark.atwood.name","created_at":"2026-07-12T06:52:12.370258Z","created_by":"Mark Atwood","updated_at":"2026-07-12T06:52:12.370288Z"}

